<font color="#FF0000">INTELLIGENCE VS. JUNQUE</font><br>
<tt>Fri Aug 15  0:39:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br>
     After 29 years, am accustomed to Military Intelligence not getting much or any respect.  I definately know the difference between A1 (very reliable, positively confirmed) and F6 (unreliable, unconfirmed) information.  I also know that &quot;information&quot; is not &quot;intelligence&quot; until it has been properly analyzed and interpreted.  I also know the difference between information obtained from prisoners and sources out in the population.  Believe it or not, some of us knew how to do our job.<br><br>
     Binh Dinh was a hotbed of Viet Minh sentiment before partition.  The VC were very strong there before being decimated during Tet.  The military defeat during Tet didn't change the underlying political preferences in the province overnight or during the following months.  Certainly, the unbelievable level of corruption in many of the National Police Detachments' commanders didn't help matters.  The locals were quite likely to look on the police as foreign occupiers who couldn't speak the area's dialect as natives.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


